|Almeida
|Designated a person who had originally lived in the town of Almeida in Portugal. The place name is from Arabic ال مائدة (al ma'idah) meaning "the plateau, the table".
|-
|Alves
|Means "son of Álvaro".
|-
|Araújo
|Denoted a person hailing from one of the many areas that bear this name in Portugal, which is of unknown meaning.
|-
|Azevedo
|
|-
|Barbosa
|Denoting a person who lived by land that contained overgrown leafy vegetation from the Portuguese word barba "leaf" + oso/osa (adjective suffix).
|-
|Bezerra
|
|-
|Borges
|Possibly from Old French burgeis meaning "town-dweller" (see Burgess). Alternately, it may have denoted someone originally from the city of Bourges in France.
|-
|Camargo
|Habitational name for someone from a place in Andalusia called Camargo.
|-
|Cardoso
|From a place name meaning "thorny" in Portuguese and Spanish, ultimately from Latin ''carduus''.
|-
|Carlos
|Derived from the given name Carlos (Spanish and Portuguese form of Charles).
|-
|Carvalho
|Means "oak" in Portuguese, perhaps originally referring to a person who lived near such a tree.
|-
|Cavalcante
|Derived from Italian cavalcare "to ride".
|-
|Cavalcanti
|Means "riding" in Italian. An occupational surname for people who worked with horses.
|-
|Coelho
|From the Portuguese word for "rabbit", either a nickname or an occupational name referring to a hunter or seller of rabbits.
|-
|Correa
|From Spanish, meaning "leather garment."
|-
|Correia
|Meaning "leather strap" or "belt", "rein", or "shoelace"; denoting a person who worked with leather products.
|-
|Costa
|Means "riverbank, slope, coast" in Portuguese, Italian and Catalan, ultimately from Latin meaning "side, edge".
|-
|De Campos
|Portuguese and Spanish variant of Campo.
|-
|De Matos
|Variant of Mata.
|-
|De Oliveira
|Means "the olive tree" in Portuguese, ultimately from Latin oliva. It indicated a person who lived near or worked with olive trees.
|-
|Dias
|Means "son of Diogo" in Portuguese.
|-
|Do Vale
|Means "valley" in Portuguese, ultimately from Latin ''vallis''.
|-
|Fernandes
|Means "son of Fernando".
|-
|Ferreira
|Denoted a person from a town named because it was near an iron mine, from Latin ferrum meaning "iron".
|-
|Furtado
|
|-
|Gimenes
|
|-
|Gomes
|From the medieval given name Gomes.
|-
|Gonçalves
|Means "son of Gonçalo" in Portuguese.
|-
|Lima
|Topographic name for someone living on the banks of the river of this name (of pre-Roman origin, probably akin to a Celtic element lemos, limos 'elm').
|-
|Maciel
|
|-
|Maia
|Habitational name from any of several places named Maia, especially one in Porto.
|-
|Martins
|Derived from the given name Martin.
|-
|Meireles
|
|-
|Melo
|Portuguese form of Merlo.
|-
|Montes
|Derived from Spanish monte "mountain".
|-
|Oliveira
|Means "olive tree" in Portuguese, ultimately from Latin oliva. It indicated a person who lived near or worked with olive trees.
|-
|Paiva
|
|-
|Pereira
|From Portuguese and Galician pereira meaning "pear tree", ultimately from Latin pirum meaning "pear".
|-
|Ribiero
|
|-
|Rocha
|Portuguese and Galician cognate of Roach.
|-
|Rodrigues
|Means "son of Rodrigo" in Portuguese.
|-
|Santos
|Means "saint" in Portuguese and Spanish, ultimately from Latin sanctus. This was a nickname for a pious person.
|-
|Schmidt
|Occupational name derived from Middle High German smit "smith, metalworker", a cognate of Smith.
|-
|Schmitz
|Variant of Schmidt, originating in the Rhine area in western Germany.
|-
|Silva
|From Spanish or Portuguese silva meaning "forest". This is the most common surname in Portugal and Brazil.
|-
|Soares
|Means "son of Suero".
|-
|Sousa
|Originally indicated someone who lived near the River Sousa in Portugal, possibly derived from Latin salsus "salty" or saxa "rocks".
